    "## 1. Introduction\n",
    "\n",
    "### 1.1 What Is Data Analysis?\n",
    "\n",
    "Data analysis is the systematic process of inspecting, cleaning, transforming, and modelling data with the objective of discovering useful information, drawing conclusions, and supporting decision-making. It encompasses a wide spectrum of techniques — from descriptive statistics that summarise what has happened, to inferential statistics that generalise findings beyond the observed sample, to predictive analytics that forecast future outcomes.\n",
    "\n",
    "In practice, data analysis follows a pipeline:\n",
    "\n",
    "1. **Data Collection** — gathering raw data from surveys, sensors, databases, or web scraping.  \n",
    "2. **Data Cleaning** — identifying and resolving errors, missing values, duplicates, and inconsistencies.  \n",
    "3. **Exploratory Analysis** — uncovering patterns, distributions, and relationships.  \n",
    "4. **Modelling** — applying statistical or machine-learning algorithms to extract knowledge.  \n",
    "5. **Interpretation** — translating quantitative findings into actionable language.  \n",
    "6. **Communication** — presenting results to stakeholders via reports, dashboards, or notebooks.\n",
    "\n",
    "---"
   ]
