    "### 1.2 What Is Exploratory Data Analysis (EDA)?\n",
    "\n",
    "Exploratory Data Analysis (EDA) is an analytical philosophy pioneered by the statistician John Tukey in the 1970s. Rather than confirming pre-existing hypotheses, EDA encourages the analyst to let the data \"speak for itself.\" The analyst examines distributions, identifies anomalies, tests assumptions, and forms hypotheses — all before fitting a formal model.\n",
    "\n",
    "Key EDA tasks include:\n",
    "\n",
    "- **Univariate analysis** — studying one variable at a time via histograms, box plots, and summary statistics.  \n",
    "- **Bivariate analysis** — examining relationships between pairs of variables via scatter plots, correlation coefficients, and grouped box plots.  \n",
    "- **Multivariate analysis** — exploring interactions among three or more variables simultaneously.\n",
    "\n",
    "EDA is not optional. Skipping it often leads to poorly specified models, undetected data quality issues, and misleading conclusions.\n",
    "\n",
