    "### 1.3 What Is Predictive Modelling?\n",
    "\n",
    "Predictive modelling is the process of using historical data to build a mathematical function that maps input features (predictors) to an output (target). Once trained, the model is applied to new, unseen data to generate predictions.\n",
    "\n",
    "Two broad families of predictive problems exist:\n",
    "\n",
    "#### Regression\n",
    "The target variable is **continuous** (e.g., exam score on a 0–100 scale). The model learns a mapping  \n",
    "`f(X) → ŷ ∈ ℝ`  \n",
    "and is evaluated with metrics such as MAE, RMSE, and R².\n",
    "\n",
    "#### Classification\n",
    "The target variable is **categorical** (e.g., performance tier: Low / Medium / High). The model learns  \n",
    "`f(X) → ŷ ∈ {class₁, class₂, …, classₖ}`  \n",
    "and is evaluated with accuracy, precision, recall, F1-score, and AUC-ROC.\n",
    "\n",
    "---"
   ]
